### Configure Canonical and Alternate URLs in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/04-functions/generate-metadata.mdx

Define canonical URLs and language/media-specific alternates using the metadata alternates property. This generates appropriate link tags in the HTML head for SEO optimization and content variant discovery. Supports canonical links, language variants, media queries, and content type alternates.

```jsx
export const metadata = {
  alternates: {
    canonical: 'https://nextjs.org',
    languages: {
      'en-US': 'https://nextjs.org/en-US',
      'de-DE': 'https://nextjs.org/de-DE',
    },
    media: {
      'only screen and (max-width: 600px)': 'https://nextjs.org/mobile',
    },
    types: {
      'application/rss+xml': 'https://nextjs.org/rss',
    },
  },
}
```

```html
<link rel="canonical" href="https://nextjs.org" />
<link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-US" href="https://nextjs.org/en-US" />
<link rel="alternate" hreflang="de-DE" href="https://nextjs.org/de-DE" />
<link
  rel="alternate"
  media="only screen and (max-width: 600px)"
  href="https://nextjs.org/mobile"
/>
<link
  rel="alternate"
  type="application/rss+xml"
  href="https://nextjs.org/rss"
/>
```

--------------------------------

### Import and use Next.js Head component for page metadata

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/02-pages/04-api-reference/01-components/head.mdx

Basic usage of the Next.js Head component to add a title to the page head. The Head component wraps elements that should be added to the document head, such as title and meta tags. This component is typically used in page components to define page-specific metadata.

```jsx
import Head from 'next/head'

function IndexPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Head>
        <title>My page title</title>
      </Head>
      <p>Hello world!</p>
    </div>
  )
}

export default IndexPage
```

--------------------------------

### Manage Next.js RootLayout metadata using the Metadata API

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/migrating/from-create-react-app.mdx

This snippet refactors the `RootLayout` to leverage Next.js's Metadata API for managing `title` and `description`. By exporting a `metadata` object, explicit `<head>` tags are removed, centralizing metadata management and enhancing SEO and web shareability through a convention-based approach.

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next'

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'React App',
  description: 'Web site created with Next.js.',
}

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        <div id="root">{children}</div>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

```jsx
